replies.body:
The problem is simple: Swain is not an ispirator. He's not sejuani. He's cold, calculator and malicious. Moreover, a frontile fighter might appeal the majority of people, but it makes 0 sense by a narrative standpoint. Noxus is a nation warring on multiple fronts. As for such, its leader (and master tactician) should be in the capital coordinating and moving his armies, not on one particular front "ripping souls out from this enemies" (wow, so coooool!).

And this has nothing to do with the consideration i have of myself, put it is purely observation:

Xerath is now a cookie cutter villain;
Diana has killed "by mistake" the elders, and not intentionally in revenge;
Poppy isn't ugly-faced yordle anymore;
Yorick isn't an outcast creepy hunchback that failed to find a partner;
Urgot lost his "fat and repulsive" archetype;

The idea those facts gave me is that Riot's narrative is pushing for pleasing the most people possible.

And to be honest reading their various statements regarding the matter, mine isn't even an "opinion". Look up at the very rioter comment i quoted in this thread:

> Swain was a champion who didn't provoke a lot of strong feelings either way, as PE just articulated very clearly. Based on a LOT of player data and feedback, old Swain not particularly interesting to a lot of players. Now there are a lot MORE players who want to find out more.

The changes Swain reiceved were made to make him more generically appealing to the great public. This involves a great narrative risk: if you build your characters not by the story you want to tell, not by your own creativity, not because they fit their personality or the world they live in, but by a **merely marketing practice to appeal the minimum common denominator, the quality of your work goes down.** And League is going strongly in that direction. And that direction is the same that gives birth to many mediocre, stereotyped anime productions right now. 

I hope this explains my words.
